message:
Yup, setting null all over the place is a bad pattern to get into. If when one sets a variable to null trying to aid the GC, I can't remember whether the JIT thus then *extends* the 'rooted' block up to there, thus actually making things much worse. Or does the JIT recognises it being a special case of setting null and ignores it. Hmm. Anyway, just don't null blindly.  

The only case I've ever had to set a local to null is within a while loop on a thread:  

void _Runner(object state)  
{  
 while(true) {  
 Command cmd = GetNextFromQueue();  
 ...action it...  
 // Must null 'cmd' here otherwise it stays   
 // alive, which has a reference to our parent,   
 // and (if when forget to Dispose it) it stays   
 // alive, and so its finalizer is never called  
 // which means we stay alive, keeping the 'cmd'  
 // alive, which means...  
 cmd = null;  
 }  
}  

Well it was something like that anyway...
